sentences: Henry Buckley Jr. aka Sadiki previously known as Pancho Kryztal (born 17 November 1971, Kingston, Jamaica), is a Jamaican-American singer, songwriter and producer.

In 1997 his self-titled debut was released on Scratchie/Mercury under the name Pancho Kryztal, to good reviews but disappointing sales as Mercury Records went through a change in its corporate structure.

Unfazed by the lack of commercial success on his first major release, he returned to Jamaica in 1998 and recorded "Rescue Me" on the Bookshelf riddim with dancehall producer Tony "CD" Kelly (Sean Paul, Lady Saw, Mr. Vegas, Super Cat).

In 1999, at the suggestion of reggae producer "Computer" Paul Henton (Shabba Ranks, Beres Hammond, Shaggy, Jimmy Cliff), he was changed his name to Sadiki – an Egyptian name meaning "faithful or loyal" (misspelled Sadeki on some earlier releases).
Sadiki again returned to Jamaica in 2001 where he scored a major dancehall hit with "Gal Dem Everytime" on the Buyout riddim for reggae producer Tony "CD" Kelly.
Within a few months of working alongside Hammond, Sadiki was selected as one of the opening acts for the elder musicians' Music is Life World Tour 2002.
In March 2007, Sadiki did a four-city tour of Japan.
"Morning's Come" was released in Japan in November 2007 (Skinny Bwoy/P-Vine Records).
The US version of Morning's Come, featuring new and unreleased tracks, was released worldwide in the Fall of 2008.
In the summer of 2009, Sadiki started work on two albums.
For 2010, the first single – "African Queen", was released on vinyl in limited quantities.
Lifeline was released in the Fall of 2010.
In 2011 the album Fi Di Dancehall (a collaborative effort with DJ Delly Ranks) was released.
In 2012 Sadiki became a member of the Legendary Rock Steady group The Tennors and also released two albums – Sadiki Meets Sandra Cross (UK Version) and his third solo album Jah Is The Only King.
In 2016 Sadiki released his fourth studio album Covered in Love.
His fifth album Blue Mountain Acoustic will be released on 1 June 2018.

In the late '90s he landed a deal with the D'arcy Wretzky (Smashing Pumpkins) and Adam Schlesinger (Fountains of Wayne/Ivy) owned label Scratchie Records, (distributed by Mercury Records).
He migrated to the United States in the late '80s and settled on Chicago's northside.
Henry Buckley Jr. aka Sadiki previously known as Pancho Kryztal (born 17 November 1971, Kingston, Jamaica), is a Jamaican-American singer, songwriter and producer.
During that year, Sadiki met reggae singer-songwriter Beres Hammond.
Within a few months of working alongside Hammond, Sadiki was selected as one of the opening acts for the elder musicians' Music is Life World Tour 2002.
On tour with Hammond for almost two years, Sadiki performed throughout the US, Japan and the Caribbean.

As well as being his singing and songwriting debut (under the name Sadiki), the album Morning's Come was also Sadiki's producing and engineering debut, as he produced or co-produced each and every track.
"Morning's Come" was released in Japan in November 2007 (Skinny Bwoy/P-Vine Records).
Within weeks of its Japan release the album hit the No. 1 spot for reggae releases at HMV record stores throughout Japan, and charted within the top 5 for sales in Tower Records stores.
The US version of Morning's Come, featuring new and unreleased tracks, was released worldwide in the Fall of 2008.
In the summer of 2009, Sadiki started work on two albums.
Lifeline was released in the Fall of 2010.
Lifeline (Skinny Bwoy/Joe Fraser Records) ***#1 Weekly Star Top 10 Chart*** No. 2 South Florida Reggae Album Charts / No. 2 New York Reggae Album Charts
